<a name="ISA.eisa"></a>
<h2>The <strong>eisa</strong> R package</h2>

<p>
The <strong>eisa</strong> package builds on the <strong>isa2</strong>
package, at makes it easy to apply ISA to
a <a href="http://www.bioconductor.org">BioConductor</a>   
<strong>ExpressionSet</strong> object. Use this package, together
with <strong>isa2</strong> if you want to analyze gene expression data.
</p>

<h3>Download and installation</h3>

<p>
Remember, that you need to install the <strong>isa2</strong>
package first, <a href="isa2.html">see more here.</a>
Then, choose a package for your platform:
</p>

<ul class="download-links">
  <li class="download-windows">
    <a href="downloads/eisa_$EISA_VERSION.zip">Microsoft Windows (all versions)</a><br/>
    Save this file, start R, and from
    the <code>Packages</code> menu choose <code>Install packages
      from local zip files</code>. Select the
    saved <code>eisa_$EISA_VERSION.zip</code> file.
  </li>
  <li class="download-osx">
    <a href="downloads/eisa_$EISA_VERSION.tgz">Mac OSX (all versions)</a><br/>
    Save this file. Then use
    the <b><code>install.packages()</code></b> function to install it;
    give the full path to the downloaded file (<code>eisa_$EISA_VERSION.tgz</code>)
    instead of just the package name, and use
    the <code>repos=NULL</code> additional argument.
  </li>
  <li class="download-source">
    <a href="downloads/eisa_$EISA_VERSION.tar.gz">Linux variants, Unix systems</a><br/>
    This is an R source package. Save this file. Then use
    the <b><code>install.packages()</code></b> function to install it;
    give the full path to the downloaded file
    (<code>eisa_$EISA_VERSION.tar.gz</code>) instead of just the
    package name, and use the <code>repos=NULL</code> additional
    argument.
  </li>
</ul>

